create

public static <T> T create(UimaContext context,
                           String classParamName,
                           Class<T> superClass)
                throws ResourceInitializationException
Take the name of a Java class from the UimaContext, instantiate the class, and initialize it (if possible).

This method was enhanced to handle instantiation of declared (member) classes so that e.g. one could instantiate an annotation handler defined as a member class in a unit test using the InstanceConsumer_ImplBase.initialize method. While this is quite convenient, make note that the referring to MyUnitTest.this in your unit test code will not work correctly in that inner class that is the test annotation handler because an instance of your unit test will be created by JUnit to run the test and another instance will be created in this method. The latter is what is available inside your inner class and is, in general, not the "this" that you want.

Type Parameters:
T - The supertype of the class which should be instantiated.
Parameters:
context - The UimaContext from which the parameter should be read.
classParamName - The name of the the UimaContext parameter containing the class name.
superClass - The superclass of the class which should be instantiated.
Returns:
An instance of the requested class, as a subtype of the supplied superclass. The instance's initialize method will be called if possible, using initialize(Object, UimaContext)
Throws:
ResourceInitializationException

checkTypeParameterIsAssignable

public static <T,U> void checkTypeParameterIsAssignable(Class<T> paramDefiningClass1,
                                                        String paramName1,
                                                        T object1,
                                                        Class<U> paramDefiningClass2,
                                                        String paramName2,
                                                        U object2)
                                           throws ResourceInitializationException
Checks that the given type parameters of the given objects are compatible. Type parameters are identified by providing the class in which the type parameter is defined, and the declared name of the type parameter. Throws a ResourceInitializationException if the type parameters are not compatible.

Type Parameters:
T - Type of the class declaring the first type parameter
U - Type of the class declaring the second type parameter
Parameters:
paramDefiningClass1 - The class declaring the first type parameter
paramName1 - The declared name of the first type parameter
object1 - The target object
paramDefiningClass2 - The class declaring the second type parameter
paramName2 - The declared name of the second type parameter
object2 - The source object
Throws:
ResourceInitializationException
